<DOC><DOCNO> AP890326-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-26-89 2243EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Kohl     03-26 0170</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Germany-Kohl,0173</SECOND><HEAD>Poll Indicates Voters Believe Kohl Should Be Replaced</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A poll indicates Chancellor HelmutKohl's popularity is at an all-time low and that most West Germanvoters want a change of leadership, a newspaper reported Sunday.   Welt am Sonntag newspaper published the results of a recent pollconducted by the Wickert Institute, which reported that 64.2percent of the voters polled wanted Kohl replaced; 35.8 percentwanted him to stay on as chancellor.   The newspaper said the survey was conducted at the request of140 companies and foundations nationwide. The institute polled2,410 registered voters in 324 localities over a seven-day period.The poll's margin of error was not given.   Kohl's conservative Christian Democratic Union party has lostground in state elections since Kohl was re-elected in 1987. Mostrecently the party lost control of the Frankfurt city government.   The loss of popularity stems in part from a scandal over theinvolvement of West German companies in an alleged Libyan chemicalweapons plant.</TEXT></DOC>